@database MailCheck
@master MailCheck:Docs/MailCheck.guide
@$VER: MailCheck v1.45
@remark What are you doing in my guide - get out!
@index Index

@NODE MAIN "MailCheck v1.45"

                           @{fg shine}MailCheck Version 1.45@{fg text}

 Important!
 ~~~~~~~~~~

 This is an intermediate release of MailCheck that enables it to function
 with YAM 2.0 preview 4 - it WILL NOT function with earlier versions of
 YAM (e.g. 1.3.5). Some of the functions may not work exactly as described 
 elsewhere in these docs!

 As you probably know the ARexx interface is not yet 100% implemented in
 YAM 2.0. This means that not all of the commands that MailCheck NEEDS to 
 function correctly are present.  The main two that are missing are those
 to send and receive mail!  Despite this I have managed to work round it
 by "feeding" keystrokes into the input stream to YAM's window.  Basically
 this simulates the pressing of the 'g' and 's' keys.  As I'm sure you can
 imagine there are some limitations of this method...
 
 * The screen on which YAM is open on must be the front screen during
   operation.  Also the YAM window must be to the front.  MailCheck will
   make every attempt to do this for you...

 * This obviously means that MailCheck cannot perform whilst iconified in
   the background :(

 Other known problems/changes...

 * There is no way (with the use of other external programs) to establish
   if a successful connection could be made to the POP3/SMTP servers.

 * A failed connection during sending will cause MailCheck to get "stuck".
   If the "After Sending Mail" ARexx function in YAM worked, I could fix
   this but until then...

 * All mail (including that on HOLD) in the outgoing folder will be sent by
   MailCheck!

 * "Interactive" mode now makes use of the HOLD function.  This works
   better than it did before with YAM 1.3.x :)

 * Filtering mail on download will cause MailCheck to report the incorrect
   number of mails received.  This is because I have had to calculate the
   mail received by comparing the quantity of mail before and after
   download.  MailCheck does not get to "look" at the incoming folder until
   filtering has taken place.
 
 There are probably more (?), but who knows...  I do not intend to spend
 time working round any of the above problems as they will be easy to solve
 when the ARexx interface is fully implemented.  Although during my tests
 this version has seemed to work very well, I would not recommend using it
 for scheduled downloads until v1.5 is released.  This will not happen
 until Marcel releases the final version of YAM 2.0 with full ARexx support.


                             @{"  " link "ReadMeFirst" 0} <-- Now read this! 


@endnode

@node "ReadMeFirst" "ReadMeFirst"

                           @{fg shine}MailCheck Version 1.45@{fg text}

 Important!
 ~~~~~~~~~~

 This page contains important information about MUIRexx problems and
 upgrading from earlier versions of MailCheck.

 Before installing MailCheck on your HD, please take a few minutes to read
 this file. After that read the "Installation" section in the AmigaGuide
 docs.

 The icons in this archive are only visible when running NewIcons. If you
 can only see little dots, then you are obviously not! Install NewIcons
 today - you won't regret it...?

 In the AmigaGuide documentation there are several links to external guides.
 Some of these may not function until MailCheck has been installed. In 
 addition to this some of the other links (those with a little square box 
 and and arrow) that require another project of mine called NetLinks.
 I am still working on this, but have some basic features up and running in 
 order to support MailCheck. Technically it's still a Beta release, but
 I've been using it for months now and have had no problems. The latest 
 version can be found for download on my web site...

                      http://www.dynamix.force9.co.uk

 It's VERY simple to install and very useful, so why not take a look...?


 MUIRexx problems!?
 ------------------

 Many people have had problems with my MUIRexx editor.  This is because I
 assumed that the MUIRexx executable file was always in the MUIRexx:
 assign. Nope! By default the installer puts it in sys:utilities/.

 This should now be fixed and if present in MUIRexx:  this executable will
 be used, but if not the default path will be used to search for the
 executable.  This seems to work okay, except for WB doesn't seem to search
 the whole path for commands - unlike the shell!

 My recommendation is to put MUIRexx in C:  or MUIRexx:.  If there are any
 other programs out there that look in sys:utilities then this may cause
 problems, but if so then copy it in here to.


 Upgrading?
 ----------

 * v1.41 users

 1) Back up your user_scripts.

 2) Back up you config file (MailCheck:MailCheck.config).

 That's it... Now install v1.45


 * v1.4 users

 1) Back up your user_scripts.

 2) Back up you config file (MailCheck:MailCheck.config).

 3) Delete the NetLinks archive from MailCheck:Extra's and get the latest
    version from my web site.

 That's it... Now install v1.45


 * v1.3 users


 1) Remove the line 'SetEnv MCStep 1' from you user-startup, before
    attempting to use v1.45.

 2) Delete GetMCTools.rexx, GetMCLibs.rexx and Mail2RW.rexx from 
    MailCheck:rexx as these have been replaced by NetLinks.

 3) Back up your user_scripts, so you don't accidently overwrite them!

 That's it... Now install v1.45


 * v1.2 users


 If you are upgrading from a MailCheck version 1.2, although not necessary I
 would strongly advise that you remove it from your HD. Please read the
 following to find out what to do...

 1) Load S:User-Startup into your favorite text editor.

 2) Remove everything between and including the lines ;BEGIN MailCheck and 
   ;END MailCheck.
 
 3) Remove these files from Rexx: 

     MailCheck.rexx
     GetMCFiles.rexx
     Mail2RW.rexx

 4) Delete (or copy if you want?) the contents of S:MCSamples/

 5) Delete S:MCSamples
 
 6) Delete S:SampleCheck

 7) Delete MailCheck.guide - where did you put it...?

 8) Delete these files from EnvArc: - if they exist!

     MCDate
     MCMail
     MCPlay
     MCSerial
     MCStep

 I would suggest that you don't simply do 'delete envarc:  MC#?', especially
 if you use MCP...?

 Your existing log file (s:MailCheck.log) will not be used by v1.45, so it's
 up to you if you want to keep it?

 That's it... Now install v1.45


                        @{"  " link "Index" 0} <-- Let's get on with it eh!? 


@endnode

