@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
 
                              @{fg shine}Introduction
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 When I first got connected to the Internet, I was immediately amazed by 
 the facility that e-mail gave me. I could send a message to someone on 
 the other side of the world and they could reply to me all within a few
 minutes.

 Then as time went by it became so laborious having to dial up my Internet
 provider and check my mail regularly - that was if I remembered!

 I though about this for some time and knowing that both Miami and YAM had
 an ARexx port I thought that it should be quite simple to write a script
 to do this for me. Automate the process with a scheduling program and that
 would be that.

 Over the last few months I have had many new ideas for this package.
 Combining these with requests from other users (not all of which I agree
 with!) here you have the results of my work.

 As I'm sure you can appreciate during testing I have dialled up to my
 Internet Provider on many occasions. I do not ask for any money from you,
 but if you use MailCheck you are required to register with me. I just want
 to know that my time and effort is not wasted.

 If MailCheck does not suit your requirements, please tell me why?

 A big thank you (in alphabetical order) goes out to the following people 
 for their assistance with this project:

          Antti Siipola, Antonio Marriott, Christer Oldhoff,
         Fred van der Zee, Gemma Bylett, Jim Hines and Karim.
 
 Lastly I would like to thank everyone who has contacted me with their
 ideas and comments. Without these people, you wouldn't be reading this
 guide...! Think about it!


                     @{fg shine}Only Amiga makes it possible...!@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "What'sNew" "What's New"

                               @{fg shine}What's New
                               ~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 Summary of changes since v1.41 (not released on Aminet):

 * MailCheck will no longer work with YAM 1.3.x. This version has been 
   designed for use and tested with YAM 2.0 preview 4.

 * Slighty updated version of MCPrefs.

 * Finnish message file included in archive.

 * All spaces in the guide are now ASCII 32. Should look okay in all fonts 
   now.

 * A few other miscellaneous bugs and typo's fixed.
 
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

                              @{fg shine}Installation
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 Okay then, in previous version of MailCheck you had an installer to do
 this for you. I only wrote this as there was more than a bit of copying
 and an assign or two to make. Things are much simpler now, so I have
 made the decision to remove it from this release.

 Firstly you must install the additional programs and libraries. Where
 possible you should follow the documentation supplied with these. In
 brief this is what you must do...

 #1  Copy reqtools.library, rexxreqtools.library and rexxtricks.library 
     to LIBS:

 #2  Copy CheckModem and Play16 to C:

 #3  Extract the InputSteam.lha archive and copy the InputStream executable
     to C:

 Now for MailCheck...

 #4  Copy the MailCheck folder and all of its contents extracted from the
     archive to somewhere on your HD.   

 #5  Add an assign in your user-startup (or with MCP etc) for Miami: and 
     MailCheck: - if they don't already exist? Something like this will 
     do...
    
     Assign Miami: Programs:Comms/Miami/
     Assign MailCheck: Programs:Comms/MailCheck/

 #6  If it doesn't exist make a directory "MailCheck:C"

 #7  Copy "OkayDokey" to "MailCheck:C/". This is VERY important, copying 
     it to "C:" will not work. There is a good reason for this... honest! 

 #8  Copy "Wait" from C: to "MailCheck:C/"

 #9  Copy "MailCheck:S/MailCheck", "MailCheck:S/LastCheck" and 
     "MailCheck:S/KillMaxTime" to S:

 #10 Double check that the 'S' protection bit of MailCheck, LastCheck and
     KillMaxTime (those copied into S:) is set. If not set this with the 
     Protect command or use DOpus etc.

 #11 Double check that the 'S' protection bit of MailCheck:Prefs/EditConfig
     is set. If not set this with the Protect command or use DOpus etc.
     
 #12 From the "Settings" menu in YAM. Select "Configuration" and select 
     "ARexx" from the left hand listview.  Set the "After getting new mail"
     script to this...
     
     MailCheck:rexx/killwait.rexx
  
     Ensure that the script type is set to ARexx and not AmigaDOS, the "Open
     console window" option is not selected and that "Wait for termination"
     is selected. These are the default settings anyway, so you probably 
     won't need to touch any of this lot.
     
 #13 Reboot your Amiga now - all is done...


 Now that was easy - wasn't it...?


@endnode

@node "Useage" "Useage"

                                @{fg shine}Useage
                                ~~~~~~@{fg text}

 The number of scripts that make up this package has grown considerably.
 Trying to explain in detail what each script does, how and why would be a
 difficult (for me) and confusing (for you) task.

 There are only three scripts which should be of interest to you, these are
 'MailCheck', 'LastCheck' and 'KillMaxTime'. They are all AmigaDOS scripts
 and can be found in your S: directory.

 Many users who have mailed me to say that MailCheck doesn't work have
 tried to execute the ARexx scripts manually
 (eg rx MailCheck:rexx/MailCheck.rexx)from the CLI. You cannot do this!

 If you get a message like this...
 "MailCheck: file is not executable" then you probably haven't read the 
 installation instruction properly and the 's' protection bit is not set! 

 Personally I have only tested MailCheck with Workbench 3.x. I can not
 however think of any reason why MailCheck won't work with all OS versions 
 from 2.04 and up. If it doesn't then let me know!

 All requesters open on the front public screen. As I'm sure you know
 this will most probably be Workbench, but depending on what patches
 and software you have running, this may not be the case.

 Below are details of each scripts function and description of operation.

  
                             @{"  " link "MailCheck" 0} MailCheck

                             @{"  " link "LastCheck" 0} LastCheck

                             @{"  " link "KillMaxTime" 0} KillMaxTime

 
@endnode

@node "MailCheck" "MailCheck"

                                @{fg shine}MailCheck
                                ~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 This script can be launched from the shell, by simple typing MailCheck.
 Alternative usage would be with a hot-key (defined with DOpus, Tool
 Manager or even FKey for example) or from an automatic scheduling 
 program such as EZCron or Recall.
 
 Only one copy of the script can be launched at any time. Attempting to
 launch a second copy will result in the second script exiting immediately.

 In version 1.4 two new CLI options have been added. These are KEEPONLINE
 and REQUEST.

 The KEEPONLINE switch overrides the 'Request to keep Miami
 on-line requester' and keeps Miami on-line even if MailCheck put it 
 on-line.

 The REQUEST switch opens a requester asking if to 'Check mail now?'.
 If you answer no the MailCheck will exit quietly with no message
 in the log.

 The STEP, KEEPONLINE and REQUEST switches can be used in any order. 
 If you want to give the STEP a value this *must* be supplied as the last
 argument. For example...

   MailCheck REQUEST KEEPONLINE STEP 4
   MailCheck STEP REQUEST KEEPONLINE
   MailCheck STEP KEEPONLINE 6
   MailCheck KEEPONLINE REQUEST 6

 The following two examples will not work...

   MailCheck STEP 4 KEEPONLINE
   MailCheck REQUEST 4 KEEPONLINE

 And now for a better explanation of those that do work:

   MailCheck STEP      ; This will give a simple toggle operation.

   MailCheck STEP 8    ; This will only execute attempt to check the mail
                         every 8th time that MailCheck is launched. 
  
   MailCheck 6         ; Like above, but every 6th time. Please note that 
                         the STEP switch is not required, but I have 
                         included this to maintain compatibility earlier
                         versions.

   MailCheck REQUEST 2 ; This will give the same results as the first 
                         example, but you will be asked if to 'Check mail
                         now?'

 For everyone who still doesn't understand, please read the example usage
 described below...

 Lets say EZCron is configured to check the mail every hour (on the hour).
 If for some reason it was not possible to connect to your Internet
 provider it would then be another hour before another attempt was made,
 not good :(.

 With the 'STEP' mode you could configure EZCron to launch MailCheck (eg
 MailCheck 6) every 10 minutes. If connection on the hour was successful,
 the following attempts (every 10 minutes) will be skipped and no attempt
 would be made until one hour later. If however the connection failed then
 an attempt will be made to check the mail after just 10 minutes. If
 successful then checking will take place at hourly intervals from this
 time. Obviously this could be 10, 20, 30, 40 or 50 minutes past the hour.
 This will continue until the connection fails, when checking will be
 stepped round again. And so on...

 If the script was launched in between scheduled checks (with no STEP
 argument or with a lower value), assuming this was successful the STEP 
 value will be reset to 1. The next scheduled check would now take place 
 one hour from this time.

 I have only discovered one downside to the "enhanced" STEP switch. If for
 example you have set EZCron to execute MailCheck with the STEP value of 8
 every 15 minutes, it would take 2 hours from power on until your mail is 
 checked :( A way to get round this is to set the default STEP value with 
 the config editor to '50' or some other high value. 

 I hope that I have explained the STEP switch well enough? Even if I 
 haven't - lets continue...  Below is a basic description of operation. In
 order to explain all of the functions I have assumed that all options are
 enabled.

 The script tests that your modem is switched on and ready for use. If it
 is not ready or is being used by another comms program (not Miami) then 
 MailCheck will exit, reporting an error in the Log File. It is assumed
 that when Miami is on-line, then it is connected to your Internet
 provider.

 Next the script checks to see if both Miami and YAM are already running.
 If they are not then they will be launched automatically. When attempting
 to launch them, the script will wait for a maximum time of 30 seconds
 (each) for the ARexx port to appear before exiting and recording the error
 in the Log File. 
 
 If both applications are launched successfully then Miami will dial your
 Internet provider. Once connected YAM will check and download all new mail
 from the POP3 mail box. After this, if there is any mail in your outgoing
 folder it will be sent to the SMTP server (optional). Before doing this a
 requester will open detailing the quantity of mail and asking you to
 confirm the send (optional). From this requester you can also enter
 'Interactive' sending, where each mail is sent to the server after
 individual confirmation.

 You will then be prompted, if to keep the connection alive (optional).
 Selecting 'Yes' will cause MailCheck to exit leaving Miami on-line. Please 
 note that if Miami was already on-line before MailCheck was launched, you
 will not be prompted to keep the connection alive, neither will you be taken
 off-line once MailCheck has finished.
 
 All details of connection are recorded in the log file
 (MailCheck:MailCheck.log) for future reference. See 'Log File' for further
 information on the Log File format.

 Other features...

  * MailCheck implements a "Maximium Time" feature which I've included as a
    'work round' to compensate for what I feel is a great deficiency in
    YAM. In the config settings you must set the maximum time that YAM is
    allowed to download and upload (if configured) mail. If YAM has not
    completed this task in the given time than Miami is taken off-line
    and quits immediately (even if configured not to do so in the config).
    The reason for my doing this is that on several occasions YAM has been
    unable to connect to the POP3 server and it just sits there waiting
    'forever'.  On another occasion my HD was full and Workbench opened a
    requester telling me of this, but yet again Miami is left on-line
    indefinitely! If you don't think that you require this feature then
    set this to a ridiculously high value in the config.

  * Both the 'Send Mail?' and 'Keep connection alive?' requesters, default
    automatically after a configurable delay. The 'Send Mail?' requester
    can be set to send all mail or none by default. The 'Keep Miami
    on-line?' requester always defaults to 'No'. The 'Interactive' send
    requesters do not default automatically and therefore should be used
    with caution.

@endnode

@node "LastCheck" "LastCheck"
   
                                @{fg shine}LastCheck
                                ~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 Like MailCheck this script can be launched from the shell, with a hot-key
 or with an automatic scheduling program. The script opens a requester
 giving details of the last successful date/time of connection, the amount
 of mail received and options to 'Check now', 'View log' or 'Cancel'.

 Selecting 'Check now' will launch MailCheck, closing the requester. If
 MailCheck is launched whilst the LastCheck requester is visible, upon
 successful connection and subsequent disconnection from the mail server,
 the requester will automatically close.

 'View log' will show the Log File with the text viewer configured in your
 settings. After pressing this button the requester will automatically open
 again.

 Obviously 'Cancel' will simply close the requester.

 Like MailCheck only one copy of LastCheck can be launched at any time.

@endnode

@node "KillMaxTime" "KillMaxTime"
   
                               @{fg shine}KillMaxTime
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 KillMaxTime can be used to temporarily disable the MaxTime protection
 period. This is useful if you've got 5 megs of mail coming in / going out
 and the MaxTime period is set to 2 minutes!

 Like MailCheck and LastCheck this script can be launched from the shell,
 with a hot key etc... When MaxTime protection has been terminated a 
 requester will open informing you of this.

 The next time you use MailCheck, MaxTime protection will automatically
 become active.  

@endnode

@node "LogFile" "Log File"

                                @{fg shine}Log File
                                ~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 The log file consists of a tab delimited text file, making it suitable for
 importing into most database or spreadsheet applications.

 Logged information includes the date, the time, the connection status and
 the quantity of mail sent/received. This is what you get...


            DAY   DATE   TIME   DURATION   IN   OUT   MESSAGE


 DAY      ; This field is reduced to 3 letters (e.g. Mon). Without reducing 
            this the log became difficult to read with a text viewer as the
            length of the week days varies too much.

 DATE     ; The date (e.g. 01-Nov-98) <--- My next birthday - hint!

 TIME     ; This is the time that the given event took place. This field 
            changes, depending if the connection was successful, or lets
            say if YAM started okay. For example if Miami failed to open,
            this field displays the time at which MailCheck attempted to
            launch Miami. If the Miami connects without problems, then this
            field will display the time at which YAM attempts to make a
            connection to the POP3 server and so on...

 DURATION ; This is the total time taken to complete the event. For events
            such as YAM failing to run, this is always set to 00:00:00.
            Normally it will display the total duration for receiving and
            sending messages. Please note this is not the 'on-line' time,
            but an indication of the time that YAM has taken to receive and
            send the mail.

 IN       ; Quantity of mail received.

 OUT      ; Quantity of mail sent.

 MESSAGE  ; This field contains a message, giving details of 'how things 
            went'. Listed below are explanations for the possible
            messages. These are from the 'default' message file and may be
            differ, depending on what message file you have installed.

  * "Error - Modem not ready". The means that the modem was either
    switched off or was being used by another program.

  * "Error - Failed to open YAM". An attempt was made to launch YAM, but
    after 30 seconds of waiting the ARexx port had not appeared.

  * "Error - Failed to open Miami". An attempt was made to launch Miami,
    but after 30 seconds of waiting the ARexx port had not appeared.

  * "Error - Miami failed to establish a connection". Miami failed to
    connect to your Internet provider. This may be because your phone line
    was in use, your provider was engaged or a protocol could not be
    established. If 'TestModemStatus' is switched off in the config, then
    you will also get this message when your modem is switched off.

  * "Error - Connection failed to POP3 server". A successful connection
    was made to your provider, but the POP3 server did not respond. The
    server is probably out of action - I get this quite a bit!
  
  * "Time out - Connection failed to POP3 server". Like above, but the
    maximum time feature of MailCheck has just saved your phone bill!

  * "Time out - Connection to POP3 server terminated". If the log reports
    that 0 mail has been retrieved then the chances are that MailCheck has
    just saved your phone bill. If it isn't 0 then mail retrieval from the
    POP3 server has just been cut-off... Whoops!
  
  * "Error - Connection failed to SMTP server". A successful connection
    was made to your provider, but the SMTP server did not respond. The
    server is probably out of action.

  * "Time out - Connection failed to SMTP server". Yet again, the maximum
    time feature of MailCheck has just saved your phone bill!
  
  * "Time out - Connection to SMTP server terminated". If the log reports
    that 0 mail has been sent then the chances are that MailCheck has just
    saved your phone bill. If it isn't 0 then your mail upload to the SMTP 
    server has just been cut-off... Whoops!
  
  * "Error - Connection failed to POP3 and SMTP servers". A successful
    connection was made to your provider, but the neither mail servers
    (POP3 or SMTP) responded. Very unlikely I would hope...?

  * "Time out - Connection failed to POP3 and SMTP servers". Where would
    you be without MailCheck...?

  * "Error - Miami dropped the line". For some reason the connection to
    your Internet Provider was lost and MailCheck could not continue. 

  * "Error - Miami quit unexpectedly". Miami was quit whilst MailCheck was
    still using it.

  * "Error - YAM quit unexpectedly". YAM was quit whilst MailCheck was still
    using it.

  * "MailCheck was successful". Like it says, all being well this is what
    you will get.

@endnode

@node "UserScripts" "User Scripts"

                              @{fg shine}User Scripts
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 The concept behind User_Scripts is so that it is possible to write
 `plug-ins` for MailCheck. At the moment there are 10 User_Scripts, each
 one being launched at key points through MailChecks execution.

 IMPORTANT NOTE!!! Whilst User_Scripts add yet more power and flexibility
 to MailCheck, at the same time they can be very dangerous... When a
 User_Script is launched MailCheck waits for the script to return before
 continuing. What I`m saying is that if the User_Script fails then so
 will MailCheck, possible leaving your modem on-line. Another point I must
 mention is that if you use the User_Scripts to play a sound module or
 another function for which MailCheck does not need to wait until it
 returns, I would suggest that you run the player as a new process (unless
 it detaches itself from the CLI...?), otherwise you may stay on-line for
 much longer than necessary! 

 In short, what I am saying is this... Ensure that you test your scripts
 thoroughly - you have been warned!

 User_Scripts must be placed in MailCheck:User_Scripts. Each one must be
 named User_Scripts_xx - where `xx` is the script number (01 to 10).

 Each User_Script is an AmigaDOS script and therefore expects DOS commands
 to execute. If you need to launch an ARexx script simply run this from
 the DOS script (e.g. sys:rexxc/rx rexx:BBSOffLine.rexx).

 Below are details of when each script is executed and an example of how
 this could be used...

  * User_Script_01 - This script is launched before your modem is tested.
    Could be used to take your BBS off-line before testing the modem.

  * User_Script_02 - This script is launched just once a day, after 6am. I
    originally set this for midnight, but found it to be annoying if I was
    working (or playing!) into the early hours. Could be used to
    automatically write a FTPMail request to get a directory listing or the
    Aminet RECENT list, like I do :)

  * User_Script_03 - This script is launched once Miami is on-line, just
    before YAM attempts to check the mail. Could be used to set your clock.

  * User_Script_04 - This script is launched if after successful checking,
    no new mail was received :( Could be used to play another sample...?

  * User_Script_05 - This script is launched once YAM has checked the mail,
    and new mail has been received. Could be used to launch an ARexx script
    to process incoming mail.

  * User_Script_06 - This script is executed after outgoing mail has been
    sent. Yet again, could play another sample...?

  * User_Script_07 - In the event that MailCheck fails in any way :( Not
    another sample, I'm running out of ideas!

  * User_Script_08 - This script is launched, just before MailCheck exits.
    Could be use to put your BBS back on-line.

  * User_Script_09 - This script is launched if YAM quits unexpectedly.

  * User_Script_10 - This script is launched if Miami quits unexpectedly or
    the line is dropped :(


@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"

                              @{fg shine}Configuration
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 There are 3 ways you could edit the MailCheck configuration file.

 1) Using my MUIRexx based @{"EditConfig" system "run >nil: execute mailcheck:prefs/editconfig"}

 2) Using Fred van der Zee's @{"MailCheckPrefs" system "run >nil: mailcheck:prefs/mailcheckprefs"}

 3) By hand using you favourite text editor (ED, CED or whatever). This way 
    is not recommended. Do this at your own risk! 

 Neither editor (EditConfig or MailCheckPrefs) can be launched whilst
 MailCheck is in use.  It is also not possible to launch both editors
 simultaneously.

 Although "MCPrefs" written by Fred van der Zee looks and functions in a 
 similar to my MUIRexx editor there are a few differences which are
 detailed @{"here" link "MCPrefs" 0}

 The editor window is split up into several tabs. These are "Mail", 
 "Connection" and "Miscellaneous". This is then divided further into
 several groups:


 Mail
 ----


  Receiving:
   
  * 'Play sample on receipt of mail'. Speaks for itself does this?

  * 'Sample name'. Hmm, tricky one is this! This requester is not accessible
    if the above option is not enabled.
 
  * 'Test Sample'. Allows you to play the selected sample.


  Sending:
 
  * 'Mail to override STEP value'. Sets the quantity of mail in the 
    outgoing folder required to override the STEP switch. For example 
    if you set this to 2 then should there be 2 or more mails waiting to
    be sent, even if the STEP value has not been reached MailCheck will
    attempts to dial up and send the mail. Set this to 0 for off. 

  * 'Send mail in outgoing folder'. Speaks for itself does this?

  * 'Request confirmation to send'. When selected you will be asked
    to confirm sending of your mail. This has no function when the above
    option is disabled.

  * 'Default requester to send'. Sets default response for the above
    requester to either 'Send all' (when enabled) or 'Cancel' (when 
    disabled).
 

 Connection
 ----------


  CheckModem:

  * 'Test modem status'. Enabling this option will cause MailCheck to 
    test is your modem is available. Try to disable this option if you keep
    getting 'Error - Modem not ready'. CheckModem does not seem to work
    with every modem properly :(

  * 'Serial device driver'. Where's your modem connected to? Select the 
    appropriate device driver from the list (eg serial.device, 
    duart.device).

  * 'Serial unit number'. Normally set to 0 unless you have a Multi I/O
    Zorro card or a HydraCOM/PortPlus.


  Miami:
 
  * 'Request to keep Miami on-line'. When enabled if MailCheck put Miami
    'on-line' then you will be asked if to keep connection alive when
    MailCheck has finished. This requester automatically defaults to 'NO'.

  * 'Quit Miami when finished'. If enable then assuming that Miami is
    off-line when MailCheck has finished, Miami will quit.


 Miscellaneous
 -------------

  LastCheck:

  * 'Use date name substitution'. If enabled then the date shown in the 
    LastCheck requester will be substituted with "earlier today",
    "yesterday", "on Monday" and so on where possible.

  * 'Log viewer'. Select your favourite text viewer, such as "More"... not!
    If you like PPMore, I've been told that using 'PPMore TAB 4' works well
    on a 640 wide screen.

  Requesters:

  * 'Time-out after ? seconds'. Sets the requester default response time.


  MaxTime:

  * 'Time-out after ? minutes'. Sets "Maximum Time" protection period, see 
    Useage for more info on this setting.

  * 'Enable 30 second warning'. When enabled, during the last 30 second of
    the MAXTIME period the screen is 'bleeped' (as set in your Sound prefs)
    every other second to warn you of this.

  Step:

  * 'Default value'. This is used to change the start-up STEP value from the
    default of 1.

  
  I think the "Save", "About" and "Quit" buttons and the menu items speak
  for themselves? In true Amiga style the editor supports drag 'n drop from
  the Workbench. I'll say no more, just try it out :)


 Environmental variables
 -----------------------

 In addition to the GUI config editor there are 2 further settings to change
 the 'Message File' and the sample player used in MailCheck and EditConfig. 
 The changes can be made permanent by adding entries in User_Script_01 or 
 copying ENV:MCFile and/or ENV:MCPlayer to ENVARC:

 The two variables are:

 * MCFile

 * MCPlayer

 Example useage as follows:

  c:setenv MCFile SiameseProxy 

 Sets the MessageFile to "MailCheck:msg/SiameseProxy.msg" (note do not 
 include the .msg extension)

  c:setenv MCPlayer c:AmiPlay 

 Sets the default sample player to "c:AmiPlay" (I made this name up!)
 
@endnode

@node "MCPrefs" "MailCheckPrefs"

                             @{fg shine}MailCheckPrefs
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 As stated elsewhere in these docs, I did not write this editor. 

 It was written by Fred van der Zee in Amiga E.  Although I have used this
 editor and feel confident that it works well, I can offer no e-mail
 support for it.  All bugs (if any found) and comments should be sent
 direct to Fred.

 @{"  " system "run >nil: sys:rexxc/rx NetLinks MAIL free@xs4all.nl*MailCheckPrefs v1.2"} <-- free@xs4all.nl


 Whilst your at it, take a look at Fred's very nice web site...

 @{"  " system "run >nil: sys:rexxc/rx NetLinks WEB http://www.xs4all.nl/~free/*REMOTE"} <-- http://www.xs4all.nl/~free 


 What's different:.

 * Doesn't require MUI or MUIRexx. 

 * Serial device drivers are not all listed.  A file called 'serlist'
   located in the MailCheck:Prefs/ directory contains the displayed
   devices.  To add a device to this list either select it with the file
   requester or enter the device name in the string requester.

 * Smaller (eg requires less memory) than EditConfig.

 * No drag 'n drop support.

 * No bubble help.

 * More keyboard support than EditConig.

 * No support for MCPlayer environmental variable.  Always plays sample
   with Play16.  Don't blame Fred for this though - I didn't tell him!

@endnode

@node "Suggestions" "Suggestions"

                              @{fg shine}My Suggestions
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 This is how I use MailCheck. I have included this section as I thought
 that it may be of use when configuring MailCheck for your own needs.

 Both Miami and YAM are configured (in the MUI settings) to start
 iconified, with an entry in the Tools menu only. This prevents them from
 suddenly popping up when I'm working on something else.

 I have configured EZCron as follows:

  LastCheck is executed in my Startup-Sequence. This way every time I reset
  (or switch on) my Amiga I can see when my mail was last checked.

  LastCheck is also configured to run every hour between 19:00 and 24:00
  during the week. This helps to keep the phone bill down in the week.

  MailCheck is configured to run every half hour (day and night) at the
  weekend. This is when I'm most likely to be at my computer. I use the
  STEP switch with a value of 4 and the REQUEST option. All being well my 
  mail is checked every 2 hours, but I can choose to stop this after a 
  crash!

 With DOpus 5.661 I have an Internet start menu where amongst everything
 else there are a couple of buttons.  One to launch MailCheck and the other
 to view the log file. Also I've configured a global hot key to launch
 LastCheck.

 I hope this gives you some ideas?

                             @{fg shine}Your Suggestions
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 I'm always looking for ideas and ways to improve my work. If you've got
 any comments, be them good or bad - let me know.

 If you have found a bug with any of the MailCheck scripts, please read the
 "Bugs" section before mailing me.

 Do you have any good quality samples which are suited to MailCheck? If the
 answer to this question is "yes" then send them to me. Please note that
 you must have permission from the copyright owner, otherwise I will not be
 able to include these in any future versions.

@endnode

@node "TheFuture" "The Future"

                                @{fg shine}The Future
                                ~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 As each week go by my thoughts on the future of MailCheck change daily.
 Without continued support from users, there may not be future versions!

 The main objective of MailCheck is to automatically retrieve e-mail as
 safely and efficiently as possible. This will always be my prime concern.

 I do however believe that I can develop the package far beyond this simple
 task. Below are some details on my changing thoughts for this package...


 Still to do
 ~~~~~~~~~~~

  * Write a GUI for MailCheck which will run as a commodity (thanks to
    MUI).
  
    This will also (possibly) replace LastCheck. The basic idea is to have
    a GUI which displays when your mail was last checked, what came in and
    what went out. There will also be some buttons to 'Check Now' and 'View
    Log'. Maybe even display the log in a small font in the GUI...? Menus
    will give access to the config editor etc... Maybe I will combine the
    config editor into this GUI. Comments and ideas please?

  * Add better support for non dial up connections (eg LAN). 

    This has been partly implemented that to SiameseProxy.  I no longer
    connect to the internet directy with my Amiga. I now have a shared 
    connection to the internet through my PC using NetProxy.  For those of
    you who don't know what I'm on about...

    I use AmiTCP (because Miami only supports 1 interface) to connect (via
    ethernet) to my PC and the PC does the dialling.  SiameseProxy fools
    MailCheck and makes it think that Miami is running and allows MailCheck
    to "talk" to Win95's Dial Up Networking to (dis)connect and establish 
    the connection status as required.

  * Add AmiTCP support.
    
    Coming soon...  Does anyone know of an easy way to check is AmiTCP is
    on-line? If so, please tell me - this is the ONLY hold up! I have some
    ideas, but they are not perfect...

  * Add Thor support.

    Despite numerous requests, this is not my top priority as *I* don't use 
    this program. If someone want's to pay me loads of money then maybe 
    I'll think again!

  * Add directory containing miscellaneous scripts related to MailCheck.

    If you have anything to add then send them to me please. I wanted to
    include some of these with this release, but time is (as always)
    against me :(

  * Automatic encryption and forwarding of incoming mail to another
    address.

    I have already written an ARexx script to do this and intend to release
    it as a User_Script very shortly.

  * Automatic reply to incoming mail (kind of like an answerphone) -
    thought this may be useful if you go away?

    Haven't started this one yet, but it would be VERY easy to write as a
    User_Script.

  * Replace all reqtools requesters with MUI ones. This would remove the
    need for 'Okay Dokey'.

  * Option to forward a list of all new mail to a different address.

    Would be easy to write as a User_Script. This would be nice as I could
    let MailCheck regularly check my mail through the day and then send me
    a list when I'm at work, so I can see what's arrived.

  * RAD disk option.

    Much work on this is already done...! I do in fact have a 99% working
    version for MC v1.2 (not much use now :-( ). More details another time!


 Not to do!
 ~~~~~~~~~~
  * Optional use of DOpus requesters, instead of Reqtools.

    Despite the fact that I just love those Magellan backdrops, I think
    that using MUI requesters is the better way to go.


 If you like what you see here, then let me know. Further development of
 this project is reliant on YOU. 

@endnode

@node "History" "History"

                                 @{fg shine}History
                                 ~~~~~~~@{fg text}

 Version 1.41  -  New config editor that does not require MUI. Written by
                  Fred van der Zee.
                  'Message' files implimented.
                  MCPlayer and MCMessage environmental variables added.
                  Requesters now have additional keyboard short-cuts.
                  NetLinks "Mail author" link added in my prefs editor.
                  LastCheck now always correctly reports the last time mail
                  was checked, even after the RTC has failed.
                  MUIRexx problems fixed. Bad assumption on my part that
                  the MUIRexx executable was always in the MUIRexx: assign 
                  dir.
                  Support for SiameseProxy added.
                  Interactive mode removed for 1 mail only.
                  Guide fixed for Multiview.
                  References in the guide to STMP corrected to SMTP - doh!?
                  Version numbering changed. No more double "points".

 Version 1.4   -  MUI based config editor to replace old reqtools one.
                  KEEPONLINE and REQUEST command line switches added.
                  MaxTime 'variable clash' fixed with MAXTIME ARexx port.
                  New 'KillMaxTime' script.
                  Script broken down into more functions and procedures.
                  Script now periodically checks the status Miami and YAM.
                  A couple of typo's in the docs corrected.
                  User_Scripts 09 and 10 added.
                  RexxSupport is now added to the library list - whoops!
                  Option to 'beep' the screen for last 30 secs of MaxTime.
                  Config file changes again (1's and 0's).
                  NetLinks support added in the guide.
                  New STEP override option for sending mail.

 Version 1.3.2 -  Several different beta copies of this were sent to
                  some users. Featured many of the changes officially in
                  v1.4.

 Version 1.3.1 -  New option to disable CheckModem.
                  Config editor updated to set above.

 Version 1.3   -  Major update, totally re-written from scratch!
                  Multiple STEP now available.
                  Send Mail option.
                  User_Scripts added.
                  Config File added, no more environmental variables.
                  Config Editor - bit rough at the moment! :(
                  Now uses Reqtools.
                  Needs RexxTricks again!
                  Maximum Time feature.
                  New options.
                  More requesters.
                  Mail buttons in guide fixed.
                  New Log File.

 Version 1.2   -  Scripts cleaned up - again!
                  New STEP mode.
                  Sample playing.         
                  Last Check script added. 
                  Install script.
                  AmigaGuide docs.
                  No longer requires RexxTricks.
                  Uploaded to the Aminet.
                  Distribution on the 'EZCron' website.

 Version 1.1   -  Scripts cleaned up (a bit) and quick docs written. 
                  Distribution with EZCron.

 Version 1.0   -  Not released, my personal use only.
                 
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs"

                                   @{fg shine}Bugs
                                   ~~~~@{fg text}

 None known at the moment. If I didn't believe in my work, I would not have
 uploaded it yet!

 Even so, there may be problems...? MailCheck works for me with the
 following configuration: (I really must update my copy of Miami!)


 Software

  * Workbench 3.0 (39.29)
  * Miami 2.1p
  * YAM 2.0 preview 4
  * Siamese RTG (TCP/IP) 
  
 Hardware

  * A1200 (Commodore)
  * Kickstart 3.0 (39.106)
  * Blizzard A1230 IV + SCSI Kit
  * 24 MB Fast Ram 
  * Hydra PCMCIA ethernet adaptor
  * Catweasel MKII floppy drive controller
  * 33,600 'no name' DVF modem


 Before mailing me try and remove any patches or hacks that are installed
 on your Amiga. If it works now then it's not my fault!

 When submitting a bug report to me, please give a brief description of
 your Amiga configuration (similar to that above). Be sure to explain
 exactly how you are using the scripts, be it manually or with a scheduling
 program.

 I will try and answer all mails within a couple of days.
 
@endnode

